Turkish diplomatic horizons are expanding
Long before Turkey began trying to join the European Union, Europe's powers longed to penetrate deep into the Turkish lockdown.
On the east bank of Bosporus, perhaps just 20 steps in Asia, stands one of the best monuments of this failed imperial ambition.
Hydarpaša railway station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Con in Neo-Renaissance style.
Well, that's what the tourist guide will tell you.
The building sits circumstantially at the end of the platforms with a tower on each corner of the facade, looking to the indistinguishable from some provincial German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slowly falling apart.
But once you get inside the vaulted cash register, you can no longer doubt the size of the business whose most western gate the station was.
The station in August 1908 was opened by the German consortium Anatoly-Bagdad Corporation.
Germany, which became involved in the game of empires lately, intended to implement its ambitions to dominate the Middle East using this railroad, which was to lead to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond the territory that is now Saudi Arabia.
But German imperial ambitions collapsed during World War I.
Their dorms were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and its irregular units.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by frozen Cold War borders, is gone
British and colonial forces advanced from Egypt and forced the Turks and their German allies from Palestine and Syria.
And bad news also came for Hydarpasha Station.
In 1917, the bombing of the ammunition train destroyed her sophisticated roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has been gradually crumbling and history has been circling it.
But today, this gateway to Anatoly and further east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Party Justice and Development - AKP - has created a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding areas, created by frozen Cold War borders, is gone.
A new policy is now being applied - Turkey is getting involved.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish Government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, Iraq and Iran, and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to review the parameters of this new policy, I boarded a night train to Ankara's Turkish capital, where I was to meet one of the leading AKP experts on foreign policy, Turkish Member Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a bumpy ride along the tracks, which reminded the old-world rhythms of the famous Night Post document, I arrived in a Turkish metropolis, designed as a new city for a secular state that wants to turn its back on its Otomanian past.
However, the AKP with its well-known Islamist roots represents a shift in the paradigm of the Turkish consensus.
She raised suspicion in the west, especially in Washington.
The taxi brought me to the main tent of AKP, an ultramodern stone and metal building, deliberately built in the developing suburbs, surrounded by half-built business houses and handle shops to power, where middle managers in business suits - men and women - meet to do early morning business.
Suat Kiniciloglu could easily be a central-right politician from almost any other European political party.
Jacket, tie, I'm sure he had Blackberry, too.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate surroundings.
The Cold War was an anomaly," he told me.
Turkey has been cut off from its lockdown.
Today, they must look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't a choice.
It had to do both.
"But surely the moment will come," I asked, "when may Turkey have to decide?"
"Turkey," he said, "it did not wish for such a decision to take place."
Then he emphasized what almost everyone I spoke to said almost by heart: Turkish relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea are equally for the benefit of Europe and the United States as well as Turkey.
With Turkey on board, it seems that Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, go east to Asia and the Middle East on these tracks.
Back at Hydarpasha Station, after another mostly sleepless night, I thought of the two German masters Herr Ritter and Herr Cona who watched this building build a hundred years ago.
How surprised they would be if they found out that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East could now be, for the most part, in Turkish hands.
And when I was waiting at the port for the ferry back through Bospor, I remembered that in those days Turkey was called "the sick man of Europe."
So it seems that at least then there was not much doubt which continent should be entitled to this fascinating country.
