"Car Bee" prevents collisions
This time, Nissan inspired the development of technology to protect against accidents in nature, specifically in bees.
This Japanese company created a robot that takes on the pattern of flying bees and thus prevents collisions.
This is Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in precipitation prevention technologies.
Engineers of the Center for Technical Progress Nissan Motor Co. robotics developed the prestigious Japanese Tokyo University in cooperation with the Centre for Advancement in Scientific and Technology Research.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, CEO of public relations for technology, research and brand development, BR23C is presented as an extension of four zones of the security shield Nissan.
The robot's task is to strengthen the ability to prevent collision in cars of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is very similar to Nissan's safety shield.
Most important, however, are composite bee eyes that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees, which allows the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
When creating this visual function, engineers designed what they called a laser localizer (Laser Range Finder).
It records obstacles located up to two metres in a 180-degree radius before BR23C, calculates the distance of the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it to a collision warning.
"At the moment the obstacle is noted, the robot mimics the bee movements and immediately changes the direction by turning the wheels to a right or even larger angle to prevent the collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is the fact that all evasive maneuvers are absolutely instinctive.
If that were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move upwards and downwards or diagonally, its movement is limited to only two dimensions and to the direction which is allowed by turning its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities as for bees.
Nissan therefore also used the rotating function in addition to acceleration and deceleration to prevent the robot from colliding.
"The device only needs to process the information every few seconds and it will be maintained according to these data.
It does not require the preservation of information or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, so it can function without interruption with only two dozen kB memory.
It may surprise you, but we don't talk about the giga or the mega in memory."
This is the first step in developing new technologies for immediate prevention of precipitation, a technology for which Nissan predicts use in serial cars in ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium ion.
Another possible future use of this technology could be the integration of the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the driver to the finish and avoid obstacles on the way.
