Benelux Government of the State Part of Fortis
The Benelux States will help the Belgian-Holland Bank of Fortis, which was the first to get into trouble in Europe because of the widespread effect of the US mortgage market crisis, by partially nationalisation: three countries will support the money and insurance institution, which also has capital participation in Hungary, with a sum of EUR 11.2 billion.
The Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments, with the participation of the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition, have agreed on this at the highest level this weekend.
Fortis is the first in the euro area to have been in a major crisis in the international financial markets, which has been spreading in waves for more than a year, and the decisions made in this case could be considered precedents from a certain point of view.
In the sense of the decision that was born on Sunday night, all three states will redeem almost half (49 percent) of the bank's assets there.
The bank will sell with absolute certainty part of its equity holdings, especially - mainly insurance - activities purchased last year from the Dutch bank ABN Amro.
Fortis' shares started to fall sharply last week, and by the second half of the week there were already serious signs of a crisis in the constitution.
But analysts agree that with their 85,000 employees, the bank is too big to let it fail.
The company's securities fell by 12 percent on Friday, to a 14-year minimum.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two thirds.
Given the current share prices, the group's total market capital value is around €14 billion, but according to the company's leaders, it is unrealistic.
Moreover, the management blames the collapse of Fortis shares in the overseas market for the adoption of a $700 billion US package plan.
By Monday, the stock has risen slightly.
On Friday the new CEO Filip Dierckx was appointed to the head of the bank.
The monetary institution was also looking for private buyers, but with a more serious offer no one has yet claimed.
The Belgian Government has previously announced that investors need not worry, they will not lose their money.
There hasn't been a panic among the bank's clients, and branches haven't been attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis has a separate branch and has also purchased several leasing companies.
Fox in the henhouse
Life and health insurance companies in America often reject the possibility of entering into an insurance contract with a candidate based on people's drug purchase data.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection programme which binds the use of drug prescription data in any case to the consent of the person concerned.
He must be in the hands of someone independent, otherwise we entrust the henhouse to the fox," quotes Washington Post Richard Dick, the author of a program designed to monitor prescription drugs.
Insurance companies shall make insurance premiums and the amounts paid in the event of claims dependent on the health of candidates and, if the risk is assessed as too large, they shall neither close the insurance with them.
Previously, they sent the person concerned for medical examinations and concluded the contract only when they knew their results.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper procedure: based on the identification number of the customer from the pharmacies, he easily finds out what medications the person has bought in the past year and a half, from which the program itself produces the disease and its health.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol lowering drugs, it refers to having virtually uncontrollably high blood fat levels, which immediately puts him in a higher-risk category.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some of them also determine the risk coefficient, so there is almost no work left for the insurance company except paperwork, although there are minor difficulties.
The drawbacks are that many medicines can be used for several purposes, some compounds are useful against migraines or hot flashes, but are also effective against depression.
These constitute a significant risk-enhancing factor for commercial insurance companies, whereas the first mentioned difficulties do not.
In order to request and process data, special companies were created to request the patient's permission before obtaining the necessary information from the pharmacy.
The authorities are now forcing them to do so, even though they have not been punished for their negligence so far.
Some companies have recently been working on the results of laboratory tests, which connect with data on the medicines used, thus providing an even more accurate picture of patients' health.
More and more companies have access to the data, while controlling their use will become increasingly difficult.
There is a special law on the protection of health data, but its effectiveness applies only to providers of health services and insurance companies.
The draft law, which gives the authorities the power to control companies specialising in data provision, is before Congress.
Richard Dick acknowledges that this is not enough: that is why he has developed his programme in such a way that the transfer of data is linked to the express consent of the person concerned.
Another thing is that he can hardly deny the permission in question, otherwise the insurance companies will not conclude a contract with him.
So the chickens are somewhat dependent on the fox's good will after all.
